<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<archimate:model xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:archimate="http://www.archimatetool.com/archimate" name="entoli-model" id="id-fca85b9eb275498c905415549bb8efb2" version="5.0.0">
  <folder name="Strategy" id="id-2b6f608ba28b4800b5e6f388e09f7550" type="strategy">
    <folder name="value stream steps" id="id-01958a00cca54e99bf5fb8b7117f767d">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="1.1 Orientation" id="id-feb72b641675413fb75053f7c0954149">
        <documentation>## Orientation&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
The issue is explored openly. Possible sources, angles and contexts are inventoried. New information may be identified.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Open-ended, exploratory&#xD;
- No source space yet fixed&#xD;
- Precedes Selection within the Exploration phase&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Open. [documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="1.2 Selection" id="id-b7b1e13c0b524faba08b585c324b2ba8">
        <documentation>## Selection&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Relevant sources are explicitly chosen. The source space is delimited and recorded. Non-selected sources are excluded.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Narrows the open source space from Orientation to an explicit, bounded set&#xD;
- Non-selected sources are formally excluded&#xD;
- Precedes Concept Inventory within the Exploration phase&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="1.3 Concept Inventory" id="id-f2259d22c1a741c6b4e901916ac51fad">
        <documentation>## Concept Inventory&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Terms, definitions and assumptions are collected and provisionally clarified, without formal structuring or modelling yet.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- No formal structuring or modelling&#xD;
- Provisional clarification only — not yet normative&#xD;
- Result feeds into Ordering&#xD;
&#xD;
[expanded from the original one-line Dutch note &quot;Begripsinventarisatie (nog zonder formele modellering)&quot; — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="1. Exploration" id="id-c1f2bd6d4ac340cba5b77ff4536182a5">
        <documentation>## Exploration&#xD;
&#xD;
**Exploration** is the phase in which an issue is opened, delimited and conceptually explored in order to identify relevant sources, concepts and hypotheses, without yet structuring or normatively recording them.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Making the problem space explicit&#xD;
- Identifying relevant sources&#xD;
- Distinguishing relevant perspectives&#xD;
- Formulating initial hypotheses&#xD;
- Collecting and clarifying concepts&#xD;
- Controlled delimitation of the source space&#xD;
&#xD;
Sub-phases:&#xD;
&#xD;
1. **Orientation**  &#xD;
   The issue is explored openly.  &#xD;
   Possible sources, angles and contexts are inventoried.  &#xD;
   New information may be identified.&#xD;
&#xD;
2. **Selection**  &#xD;
   Relevant sources are explicitly chosen.  &#xD;
   The source space is delimited and recorded.  &#xD;
   Non-selected sources are excluded.&#xD;
&#xD;
3. **Concept Inventory**  &#xD;
   Terms, definitions and assumptions are collected and provisionally clarified.  &#xD;
   No formal structuring or modelling yet.&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- Interpretation permitted&#xD;
- Exploration possible (in Orientation)&#xD;
- No formal structural enforcement yet&#xD;
- No normative status yet&#xD;
- Result is preparatory input for Ordering&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Exploratory&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime:&#xD;
- Orientation: Open&#xD;
- Selection &amp; Concept Inventory: Selection-bound [not a canonical Source-regime position — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="2.1 Conceptual Restructuring" id="id-388b36e9b090429cba462376c5896934">
        <documentation>## Conceptual Restructuring&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Starting point: Concept Inventory. Purpose: from raw input → to coherent conceptual units.&#xD;
&#xD;
For data:&#xD;
- Abstracting concepts&#xD;
&#xD;
For work:&#xD;
- Clustering hypotheses into THEMEs&#xD;
&#xD;
### Activities&#xD;
- Abstracting concrete terms into types&#xD;
- Generalising specific cases&#xD;
- Making implicit categories explicit&#xD;
- Resolving synonymy&#xD;
- Merging overlapping concepts&#xD;
- Eliminating redundancy&#xD;
- Sharpening scope&#xD;
- Distinguishing between type, role and instance&#xD;
&#xD;
### What happens here&#xD;
Variation is reduced and meaning is lifted to a higher level of abstraction. This is the phase in which the concept field and the work are &quot;cleaned up&quot;.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="2.2 Structure Formulation" id="id-d0beb6222340400cb9d370777a98a3a9">
        <documentation>## Structure Formulation&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Question: how do the concepts formally relate to each other?&#xD;
&#xD;
### Activities&#xD;
- Formulating facts&#xD;
- Making roles explicit&#xD;
- Determining cardinalities&#xD;
- Formulating necessary and sufficient conditions&#xD;
- Modelling constraints&#xD;
&#xD;
Coherence is enforced here.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="2.3 Reduction &amp; Consistency" id="id-a9bb9c9fb0574bc3beb831698ea1ea1f">
        <documentation>## Reduction &amp; Consistency Enforcement&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Overlap is eliminated, redundancy removed and internal coherence checked. The structure is made minimal and coherent.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Follows Structure Formulation within the Ordering phase&#xD;
- Produces the final, coherent structure handed off to Recording&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="2. Ordering" id="id-537012ff381c4ef4be18a3b53037a397">
        <documentation>## Ordering&#xD;
&#xD;
**Ordering** is the phase in which explored and selected input is converted into a coherent, consistent and structurally explicit structure suitable for normative recording.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Reducing variation&#xD;
- Making implicit coherence explicit&#xD;
- Correctly positioning abstraction levels&#xD;
- Enforcing internal consistency&#xD;
- Preparing the structure for normative ratification&#xD;
&#xD;
Sub-phases:&#xD;
&#xD;
1. **Conceptual Restructuring**  &#xD;
   Concepts, hypotheses or work items are abstracted, grouped and deduplicated.  &#xD;
   Variation is reduced and fundamental conceptual units are determined.&#xD;
&#xD;
2. **Structure Formulation**  &#xD;
   Relations, hierarchy and dependencies are made explicit.  &#xD;
   For data: formal modelling (e.g. NIAM).  &#xD;
   For work: THEME → IMPROVEMENT → WORK-TASK structure.&#xD;
&#xD;
3. **Reduction &amp; Consistency Enforcement**  &#xD;
   Overlap is eliminated, redundancy removed and internal coherence checked.  &#xD;
   The structure is made minimal and coherent.&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- Interpretation within a closed source space is permitted&#xD;
- No new external content&#xD;
- No normative status&#xD;
- Iterative in nature&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Structural&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="3.1 Ratification &amp; Formal Fixation" id="id-6070b4f616d243239c1ec49c0d93044c">
        <documentation>## Ratification &amp; Formal Fixation&#xD;
&#xD;
**Ratification &amp; Formal Fixation** is the sub-phase within S;pecification in which an ordered structure or behaviour description is explicitly declared valid and recorded exactly and unambiguously.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Normatively confirming one chosen variant&#xD;
- Explicitly recording scope and mandate&#xD;
- Freezing terminology and definitions&#xD;
- Formulating structure and behaviour exactly (e.g. logical data model, Gherkin)&#xD;
- Recording version and references&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- No new structure or content&#xD;
- No further interpretation&#xD;
- Analysis turns into norm&#xD;
- The artefact becomes a stable reference point&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Normative&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="3.2 Making Testability Explicit" id="id-720ae6fa7fc34c368b9e45e7fa97de1c">
        <documentation>## Making Testability Explicit&#xD;
&#xD;
**Making Testability Explicit** is the sub-phase within Recording in which the normatively established artefact is made checkable and verifiable.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Explicitly formulating acceptance criteria&#xD;
- Recording traceability to source artefacts&#xD;
- Clarifying the relationship between norm and test mechanism&#xD;
- Making consistency checkable&#xD;
- Optionally recording formal validation rules&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- No new content or structure&#xD;
- No new norm formation&#xD;
- Strengthens checkability and traceability&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Normative (specification of test conditions)&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime:&#xD;
- Canon-bound&#xD;
- Optionally Input-bound for formal validation checks</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="3.3 Publication &amp; Anchoring" id="id-7297e979e65e449f8889ce5085d7f2c9">
        <documentation>## Publication &amp; Anchoring&#xD;
&#xD;
**Publication &amp; Anchoring** is the sub-phase within Recording in which the normatively established and tested artefact is formally positioned within the ecosystem.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Officially registering the artefact (version, date, owner)&#xD;
- Making positioning within the value stream and workspace explicit&#xD;
- Recording relations with other artefacts&#xD;
- Making access and validity known&#xD;
- Making status explicit (draft, established, superseded)&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- No substantive change&#xD;
- No new norm formation&#xD;
- The artefact receives formal status and governance context&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Normative (institutionalisation of the norm)&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="3. Specification" id="id-65234a3ade134f81ae3b8082d8352e46">
        <documentation>## Recording&#xD;
&#xD;
**Recording** is the phase in which an ordered structure or behaviour description is converted into a normative, testable and formally anchored artefact within the ecosystem.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Explicitly declaring the ordered structure as valid&#xD;
- Recording behaviour and definitions exactly and unambiguously&#xD;
- Safeguarding testability and traceability&#xD;
- Formally positioning the artefact within governance&#xD;
&#xD;
Sub-phases:&#xD;
&#xD;
1. **Ratification &amp; Formal Fixation**  &#xD;
   One chosen variant is normatively confirmed. Scope and mandate are made explicit.&#xD;
&#xD;
2. **Formal Fixation**  &#xD;
   Structure and behaviour are formulated exactly and stably (e.g. logical data model, Gherkin). Terminology is frozen.&#xD;
&#xD;
3. **Making Testability Explicit**  &#xD;
   Acceptance criteria, validation rules and traceability are recorded so that testing is possible.&#xD;
&#xD;
4. **Publication &amp; Anchoring**  &#xD;
   The artefact receives formal status (version, owner, positioning, validity) within the ecosystem.&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- No new structure or domain content&#xD;
- No further exploration or interpretation&#xD;
- Analysis turns into norm&#xD;
- The artefact becomes the reference point for realisation and testing&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Normative&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="4.1 Construction" id="id-358edcf4a1554c39990c94c3abe817cc">
        <documentation>## Construction&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Building up the intended structure or solution.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Concrete creation  &#xD;
- Direct production  &#xD;
- Artefact-oriented  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- Writing code  &#xD;
- Creating database tables  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Setting up a governance process  &#xD;
- Setting up a business-case structure  </documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="4.2 Integration" id="id-5f2733153961480388621c752ed99bb5">
        <documentation>## Integration&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Connecting realised components into a coherent whole.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Relation-oriented  &#xD;
- System-oriented  &#xD;
- Aligning interfaces  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- API integrations  &#xD;
- Service integration  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Aligning processes  &#xD;
- Bringing policy lines together  &#xD;
</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="4.3 Verification" id="id-05245e43762d4ecbbcfe3eba4149d3cd">
        <documentation>## Verification&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Checking whether the realised structure functions in accordance with the recorded meaning.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Testing&#xD;
- Conformity-oriented  &#xD;
- Traceable back to Recording  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- Testing against requirements  &#xD;
- Unit and integration tests  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Process validation  &#xD;
- Compliance check  </documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="4. Realisation" id="id-97cbf8471d0d489fba13c9e3f2d14bd1">
        <documentation># Realisation&#xD;
&#xD;
**Realisation** is the phase in which established meaning is converted into a working, applicable or executable structure within the workspace.&#xD;
&#xD;
Where **Recording** makes meaning binding,  &#xD;
**Realisation** makes that meaning operational.&#xD;
&#xD;
Realisation produces realising artefacts.&#xD;
&#xD;
## Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Converts bindingly established meaning into operation  &#xD;
- Creates executable, applicable or working structures  &#xD;
- Reduces interpretive latitude  &#xD;
- Increases concreteness and specificity  &#xD;
- Shifts focus from &quot;what must hold&quot; to &quot;what works&quot;  &#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Realising&#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## Examples (value-stream generic)&#xD;
&#xD;
- Implementing software code  &#xD;
- Setting up a workflow or process  &#xD;
- Configuring a runtime environment  &#xD;
- Building a data model in a database  &#xD;
- Implementing a governance mechanism  &#xD;
- Setting up an organisational structure  &#xD;
- Realising an investment structure  &#xD;
&#xD;
[The original Dutch text embedded a duplicate &quot;4.4 Operationalisatie&quot; sub-section here, describing content that belongs to the separate &quot;6. Operationalisation&quot; phase (id-1a741fb4…), where it has now been documented properly. That duplicate has been removed from here to avoid two conflicting copies of the same content — see alignment report.]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="5.1 Performing Comparison" id="id-86005bc0d7204e6c9e83b9aab56e2fe5">
        <documentation>## Performing Comparison&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
The realised or specified artefact is compared against the established test basis (the recorded norm from Recording).&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Follows Establishing Test Basis [not itself modelled — see alignment report]&#xD;
- Produces the raw comparison result consumed by Qualifying Deviations and Making Judgment Explicit&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="5.2 Making Judgment Explicit" id="id-e8af859499b34e57a11972b4d6f49b1f">
        <documentation>## Making Judgment Explicit&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
The outcome of the comparison is turned into an explicit, traceable judgment on whether the artefact meets the norm.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Makes the judgment traceable to the specific criteria it is based on&#xD;
- Prepares any necessary escalation&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Validating&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="5.3 Reporting" id="id-b64ecc3211a14ac6b2aa25ffda668cb8">
        <documentation>## Reporting &amp; Feedback&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
The judgment and any identified deviations are reported and fed back to the relevant stakeholders and, where applicable, to the preceding phases.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Closes the Testing phase&#xD;
- Supports traceability and audit of the testing outcome&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="5. Testing" id="id-647ee4ad868c438ba52f62a416598df7">
        <documentation>## Testing&#xD;
&#xD;
**Testing** is the phase in which a realised or specified artefact is assessed against an established norm.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Determining whether an artefact meets the norm&#xD;
- Making deviations explicit&#xD;
- Making the judgment traceable&#xD;
- Preparing any escalation&#xD;
&#xD;
Sub-phases:&#xD;
&#xD;
1. Establishing Test Basis  &#xD;
2. Performing Comparison  &#xD;
3. Qualifying Deviations  &#xD;
4. Making Judgment Explicit  &#xD;
5. Reporting &amp; Feedback&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Validating&#xD;
&#xD;
[GAP: the model only has elements for sub-phases 2, 4 and 5 (Performing Comparison, Making Judgment Explicit, Reporting). Sub-phases 1 (Establishing Test Basis) and 3 (Qualifying Deviations), listed here, have no corresponding ValueStream element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="7.1 Decision-making" id="id-16fe114b5e2a421686fa098c7f445885">
        <documentation>## 6.1 Decision-making&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
A formal or implicit decision that the realised structure may come into effect.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Mandate or authority is exercised  &#xD;
- Acceptance is ratified  &#xD;
- Risk transition is acknowledged  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- Go-live decision  &#xD;
- Change approval  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Formal ratification of new policy  &#xD;
- Investment approval  &#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound. [corrected: this element previously carried the documentation for &quot;4.1 Construction&quot; — a copy-paste error in the source model; see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="7.2 Activation" id="id-0e1ce8ea8486489fb1d62b4fdc610900">
        <documentation>## 6.2 Activation&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Actually bringing the structure into effect, technically, organisationally or legally.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Concrete transition to active status  &#xD;
- Change of runtime or practice conditions  &#xD;
- No longer hypothetical  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- Deployment to production  &#xD;
- Activating a feature flag  &#xD;
- Making configuration live  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Starting a new process  &#xD;
- Rolling out an organisational structure  &#xD;
- Making a contract take effect  &#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Input-bound. [corrected: this element previously carried the documentation for &quot;4.2 Integration&quot; — a copy-paste error in the source model; see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="7.3 Guidance" id="id-3e54533b13704a56af91a66bf67b5763">
        <documentation>## 6.3 Guidance&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Guiding the transition from the old situation to the new one.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Transition measures  &#xD;
- Phase-out or migration  &#xD;
- Stabilisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- Data migration  &#xD;
- Parallel run  &#xD;
- Cutover  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Handover period  &#xD;
- Phased rollout  &#xD;
- Onboarding those involved  &#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Open. [corrected: this element previously carried the documentation for &quot;4.3 Verification&quot; — a copy-paste error in the source model; see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="7.4 Consolidation" id="id-2a2576ea2a4846dcbd96586712f32636">
        <documentation>## 6.4 Consolidation&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Anchoring the new structure as regular, ongoing reality.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Monitoring and stabilisation  &#xD;
- Anchoring in policy or practice  &#xD;
- Normalisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Software example&#xD;
&#xD;
- Monitoring in production  &#xD;
- Incident management  &#xD;
- Performance optimisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Non-software&#xD;
&#xD;
- Evaluation of the new process  &#xD;
- Formal inclusion in governance  &#xD;
- Structural budgeting  &#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound. [corrected: this element previously carried the documentation for &quot;4.3 Verification&quot; — a copy-paste error in the source model; see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="7. Operationalisation" id="id-1a741fb46b3d410c8eda68bf5a6a5fdc">
        <documentation># Operationalisation&#xD;
&#xD;
## Definition&#xD;
&#xD;
**Operationalisation** is the phase in which a realised and verified structure is formally brought into effect within the intended context, thereby becoming operative reality.&#xD;
&#xD;
Where:&#xD;
&#xD;
- **Recording** makes meaning binding,  &#xD;
- **Realisation** makes that meaning work,  &#xD;
&#xD;
**Operationalisation** makes the working structure actually take effect in practice.&#xD;
&#xD;
Operationalisation marks the transition from:&#xD;
&#xD;
> working structure in the workspace  &#xD;
> to  &#xD;
> operative structure in reality.&#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Context transition (from workspace to practice)  &#xD;
- Formal or de facto activation  &#xD;
- Change of operative reality  &#xD;
- Can have legal, organisational or technical consequences  &#xD;
- Is less reversible than realisation  &#xD;
- Often has governance implications  &#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## Positioning in the generic value stream&#xD;
&#xD;
1. Exploration  &#xD;
2. Ordering  &#xD;
3. Recording  &#xD;
4. Realisation  &#xD;
   - Construction  &#xD;
   - Integration  &#xD;
   - Verification  &#xD;
5. Testing  &#xD;
6. Operationalisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
Operationalisation thus follows after realisation and testing. [corrected: the original Dutch text listed a five-phase sequence with &quot;Verantwoording&quot; (Accountability) as a Realisation sub-phase — this does not match the six top-level Development phase positions used elsewhere in this model (Exploration/Ordering/Recording/Realisation/Testing/Operationalisation); see alignment report]&#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
# Sub-phases of Operationalisation&#xD;
&#xD;
A generic four-part model, applicable across software, governance, organisation, investment, etc. These four sub-phases correspond to the canonical Operationalisation sub-phases in entoli-concepts.md: Decision-making (Canon-bound), Activation (Input-bound), Guidance (Open), Consolidation (Canon-bound).&#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## 6.1 Decision-making&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
&#xD;
A formal or implicit decision that the realised structure may come into effect.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Mandate or authority is exercised  &#xD;
- Acceptance is ratified  &#xD;
- Risk transition is acknowledged  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Go-live decision  &#xD;
- Change approval  &#xD;
&#xD;
**Non-software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Formal ratification of new policy  &#xD;
- Investment approval  &#xD;
- Governance decision to introduce  &#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## 6.2 Activation&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
&#xD;
Actually bringing the structure into effect, technically, organisationally or legally.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Concrete transition to active status  &#xD;
- Change of runtime or practice conditions  &#xD;
- No longer hypothetical  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Deployment to production  &#xD;
- Activating a feature flag  &#xD;
- Making configuration live  &#xD;
&#xD;
**Non-software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Starting a new process  &#xD;
- Rolling out an organisational structure  &#xD;
- Making a contract take effect  &#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## 6.3 Guidance&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
&#xD;
Guiding the transition from the old situation to the new one.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Transition measures  &#xD;
- Phase-out or migration  &#xD;
- Stabilisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Data migration  &#xD;
- Parallel run  &#xD;
- Cutover  &#xD;
&#xD;
**Non-software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Handover period  &#xD;
- Phased rollout  &#xD;
- Onboarding those involved  &#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## 6.4 Consolidation&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
&#xD;
Anchoring the new structure as regular, ongoing reality.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
&#xD;
- Monitoring and stabilisation  &#xD;
- Anchoring in policy or practice  &#xD;
- Normalisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Monitoring in production  &#xD;
- Incident management  &#xD;
- Performance optimisation  &#xD;
&#xD;
**Non-software**&#xD;
&#xD;
- Evaluation of the new process  &#xD;
- Formal inclusion in governance  &#xD;
- Structural budgeting  </documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="6. Recording" id="id-6ea14b588b3a421a863ef753cbc4678e">
        <documentation>## Accountability&#xD;
&#xD;
**Accountability** is the phase in which the process, the choices made and the judgments reached are made explicit, transparent and traceable within the ecosystem.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose:&#xD;
- Giving insight into the steps followed and choices made&#xD;
- Safeguarding traceability to source artefacts&#xD;
- Making overviews and documentation available&#xD;
- Supporting transparency and governance oversight&#xD;
&#xD;
Sub-phases:&#xD;
&#xD;
1. **Documenting**  &#xD;
   Relevant decisions, assumptions and considerations are explicitly recorded.&#xD;
&#xD;
2. **Making Traceability Explicit**  &#xD;
   Relations between artefacts, norms and realisations are made insightful (e.g. matrices, traceability overviews).&#xD;
&#xD;
3. **Contextualising**  &#xD;
   Positioning within the value stream, governance and mandate is clarified.&#xD;
&#xD;
4. **Publishing &amp; Sharing**  &#xD;
   Accountability information is made available to relevant stakeholders.&#xD;
&#xD;
Characteristics:&#xD;
- No new norm formation&#xD;
- No new structure formation&#xD;
- No new evaluation&#xD;
- Transparency about what has already taken place&#xD;
&#xD;
Interpretation Mode: Explanatory&#xD;
&#xD;
Source-regime: Canon-bound&#xD;
&#xD;
[See the UNMAPPED note on this element's name: this phase is not one of canon's six Development phase positions and is mis-numbered &quot;5&quot;, colliding with Testing]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="6.1 Documenting" id="id-c59e63d05e254d58bc3c445846637346">
        <documentation>## Documenting&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Relevant decisions, assumptions and considerations are explicitly recorded.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- First sub-phase of Accountability&#xD;
- Produces the raw record consumed by Making Traceability Explicit&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="6.2 Making Traceability Explicit" id="id-26f09401b59f4565a9a504171f032d11">
        <documentation>## Making Traceability Explicit&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Relations between artefacts, norms and realisations are made insightful, e.g. via matrices or traceability overviews.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Builds on the record produced by Documenting&#xD;
- Precedes Contextualising&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="6.3 Contextualising (Target Audience)" id="id-79ad131084184f939ca089447aeb2212">
        <documentation>## Contextualising&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Positioning within the value stream, governance and mandate is clarified for the intended target audience.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Follows Making Traceability Explicit&#xD;
- Precedes Publishing&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ValueStream" name="6.4 Publishing" id="id-a61ccf1fcb52413ba576ad262408d018">
        <documentation>## Publishing &amp; Sharing&#xD;
&#xD;
### Definition&#xD;
Accountability information is made available to relevant stakeholders.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Characteristics&#xD;
- Closes the Accountability phase&#xD;
- No new content is introduced — purely dissemination of what was already documented and contextualised&#xD;
&#xD;
[documentation newly defined for this element — see alignment report]</documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:Capability" name="Normative Specification" id="id-66d4eb74005f45abbf27ac809e8534ea">
      <documentation>The ability of the ecosystem to translate structured knowledge into binding, testable, and enforceable directives that govern realisation.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose&#xD;
  To create normative clarity and enforceable intent for implementation and validation.&#xD;
&#xD;
Scope&#xD;
  Requirement specification&#xD;
  Logical data modelling&#xD;
  Constraint definition&#xD;
  Testability design</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:Capability" name="Knowledge Structuring" id="id-4732496fbe224a74904e6af2c58f8517">
      <documentation>The ability of the ecosystem to transform acquired knowledge into coherent, consistent, and explicit structural representations without introducing normative commitment.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose&#xD;
  To create shared understanding and semantic coherence as a prerequisite for specification.&#xD;
&#xD;
Scope&#xD;
  Concept identification and definition&#xD;
  Relationship modelling&#xD;
  Structural consistency and reduction&#xD;
  Model consolidation</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:Capability" name="Knowledge Acquisition" id="id-ce7573af6de14faca976848c20aefcba">
      <documentation>The ability of the ecosystem to identify, obtain, and contextualise relevant knowledge from internal and external sources under explicit source constraints.&#xD;
&#xD;
Purpose&#xD;
  To ensure that all downstream structuring and specification activities are grounded in traceable and explicitly selected sources.&#xD;
&#xD;
Scope&#xD;
 Source identification and selection&#xD;
 Source ingestion and preparation&#xD;
 Interpretation of source content (non-normative)&#xD;
 Hypothesis formation under uncertainty&#xD;
 Realisation (Behavior elements)&#xD;
 Source Selection&#xD;
 Source Interpretation&#xD;
 Hypothesis Formulation&#xD;
&#xD;
</documentation>
    </element>
  </folder>
  <folder name="Business" id="id-a2041084116e42ea80c1b0c940e528c9" type="business">
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Entoli-agent" id="id-a21ac844b75946b0b94ab3450c81ed27"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Agent-capability" id="id-fc519c97c3c04fb3b43a50b72f0aef38"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Execution" id="id-6d970dab1a4645d1982858c7a1096e69">
      <documentation>An Execution is a runtime instance derived from an Execution Step Specification. It is the container in which an Instruction Set is carried out and in which Execution Steps are recorded.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Execution Step Specification" id="id-0a67e6f41ebb45b9b7a3fc306bc08cd1"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Instruction Set" id="id-a4319ee116ab41dda18d476242ca88da"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Artifact-function-axis" id="id-e252cb7dde504e91b65fb22a5cc3cf23"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Entoli-artifact" id="id-4e0f720907c34ad186ec8a6958817d41"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Source-regime" id="id-fe950c3ebad04932a87cb572b191e4ff"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Development phase" id="id-85976594d9b24ea68b752ad1b5cd8719"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Interpretation Mode" id="id-3969a1acce774516911bb973b0ff59ee">
      <documentation>Interpretation Mode is the classification axis that specifies, per agent-intent, within what interpretive boundaries the LLM is permitted to operate when executing the task. [renamed from non-canonical &quot;Intervention Type&quot; — see alignment report]</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Mode of operation" id="id-b0aa2469bd5c465bacc1122e45254a86"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Agent-capability" id="id-7a697edbd9ca441483bfab6dcdb88633"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Value stream phase" id="id-c4110ee27b2644a59ca54a4c3ad15350"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Value stream" id="id-d568ba0e747140fe9548894e6fc784bc"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Normative artifact" id="id-b7cb33c7b50e48dabb3f0d830de8698f"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Semantic Model" id="id-1fa6202fbcb84810a487e731d399058b"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Semantic Scope" id="id-2a6ed230ccee40588fafaaf91e026a3c">
      <documentation>A Semantic Scope is an explicitly defined, context-specific subset of the Semantic Model, selected for use by a specific agent contract or coordination context.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:Product" name="Entoli-ecosystem" id="id-13cb9b3b65d24d1fb85aabf9085a47a5"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Semantic Foundation [UNMAPPED — no canonical Domain Element equivalent]" id="id-80ac7471a6494f0ca5750484251b474f"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Entoli-concept" id="id-df1eaf40fb2e46b48b5675974dfa3b70"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Relationship" id="id-9c775a49c62f4d49a90673446cec6a64">
      <documentation>A relationship is an explicit, directed semantic link between two elements. Relationships carry the meaning of the graph; elements without relationships have meaning, but not structure.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Element" id="id-a248b6e4d5a04c6c995cc9ecb4872d2e">
      <documentation>An element is an explicitly defined, named unit of meaning within the Entoli semantic graph. Every entry in this register is an element. Elements are distinguished by their element classification and by the relationships they hold to other elements.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Domain Element" id="id-70b0088bd5f64183a6ef17dbcff1bef2"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Para Element" id="id-a1833eb002504e44aea29c041263a636">
      <documentation>Paradata — “what happened around this thing”&#xD;
&#xD;
Paradata describes the process, interaction, or execution context involving the artifact.&#xD;
&#xD;
It is:&#xD;
&#xD;
dynamic&#xD;
execution- or usage-related&#xD;
observational&#xD;
&#xD;
Examples:&#xD;
&#xD;
who accessed it&#xD;
how it was processed&#xD;
token usage in generation&#xD;
execution timestamp&#xD;
validation result&#xD;
transformation history</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Classification Element" id="id-0498a286a8834a74abe40965a70ef882">
      <documentation>A classification element is a specialization of Element that represents a taxonomy or classification concept. Classification elements provide structured axes along which other concepts can be categorized, grouped, or typed. They form the basis for governance, filtering, and structured retrieval within the semantic model.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Position Element" id="id-beac072548d34fdabe5c48ace38edb7f">
      <documentation>A position element is a specialization of Element that expresses a location, rank, or standing within a structured dimension such as a hierarchy, sequence, or coordinate system. Position elements define where something stands in relation to other elements along a defined axis.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Actor Element [UNMAPPED — not a canonical Element classification]" id="id-f59b5f9ddf7a418f9dda736ba2ae8bf8">
      <documentation>An actor element is a specialization of Element that represents an agent, role, or party capable of performing actions or participating in processes. Actor elements define the who in the semantic model — the entities that act, decide, or take responsibility within the Entoli ecosystem. NOTE: the canon defines exactly four Element classifications (Domain, Classification, Position, Para). &quot;Actor Element&quot; is not among them and has no canonical equivalent; see alignment report.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Validity Element [UNMAPPED — not a canonical Element classification]" id="id-1752cab081274e18995791ebceaf97b7">
      <documentation>A validity element is a specialization of Element that expresses a validity state, condition, or assessment. Validity elements classify whether something holds, is in force, has been assessed, or is considered truthful within the semantic context. They are used to qualify the epistemic or normative status of concepts and relationships. NOTE: the canon defines exactly four Element classifications (Domain, Classification, Position, Para). &quot;Validity Element&quot; is not among them and has no canonical equivalent; see alignment report.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Object Element [UNMAPPED — not a canonical Element classification]" id="id-e0fde956aedf4badbc0d37db418f6e4c">
      <documentation>An object element is a specialization of Element that represents a concrete or abstract thing, artifact, or entity that can be acted upon or referred to. Object elements are the what in the semantic model — the subjects and objects of semantic relationships, distinct from actors, positions, or classification axes. NOTE: the canon defines exactly four Element classifications (Domain, Classification, Position, Para). &quot;Object Element&quot; is not among them and has no canonical equivalent; see alignment report.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Entoli-artifact" id="id-9da5117d824b49139c522a80e0842913">
      <documentation>An artifact is an explicitly created, durable work product produced or consumed by an Entoli agent within a project workspace. An artifact is either a normative artifact (prescribing rules or norms) or a business artifact (recording content, decisions, or deliverables). Artifacts are the primary units of value exchange within a value stream phase. NOTE: the &quot;normative vs. business&quot; split used here is not the canonical sub-classification — canon classifies Entoli-artifact via the artifact-function-axis (Governance / Directive / Implementing / Structuring / Registering artifact); see alignment report.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Policy (scope) [UNMAPPED — no canonical Domain Element; canon references &quot;policies&quot; informally within Agent-contract/Agent-charter]" id="id-e4a9254e102044fd9aa8de02b2ac4543">
      <documentation>A policy (scope) is a set of explicit rules, constraints, and permissions that governs what an Entoli agent is allowed to do within a defined workspace scope. It determines which artifacts may be accessed, which operations are permitted, and under which conditions the agent may act. A policy (scope) is applied by the agent at runtime to enforce governance boundaries.</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:Product" name="llm-constraints.rules.yaml" id="id-963f2aa34316454fa2b28022048c0696">
      <documentation>foundations\.injection-sources\rules\llm-constraints.rules.yaml</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:Product" name="system-constraints.md" id="id-2dbcaec7d1c3495bafbc6b15b2c159e7"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="llm-execution-configuration [UNMAPPED — likely a technical realisation of the canonical Execution file, not itself a distinct canon concept]" id="id-5ce9924ee4a2498b98b13bdf9cfe5d4a"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="external-resource [UNMAPPED — no canonical Domain Element; corresponds informally to the External-source-bound source space of Source-regime]" id="id-3b5fd0ff2997473bb92ee905634e8af1">
      <documentation>OpenAI&#xD;
Google&#xD;
Anthropic</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="private-resource [UNMAPPED — no canonical Domain Element; corresponds informally to the Workspace-bound source space of Source-regime]" id="id-36466e4eb8444f2d8ac075def55235a4"/>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="entoli-resource [UNMAPPED — no canonical Domain Element; corresponds informally to the Canon-bound source space of Source-regime]" id="id-34a62ff77db64291a32395b192564d8d">
      <documentation>example: Oloma (hosted by BaseTide)</documentation>
    </element>
    <element xsi:type="archimate:BusinessObject" name="Language Intelligence Resource [UNMAPPED — no canonical Domain Element; canon refers only generically to &quot;the LLM&quot;, and this duplicates the &quot;large language model&quot; data object elsewhere]" id="id-99ad1258e4564f9b8310b7435ceff52b"/>
  </folder>
  <folder name="Application" id="id-1b7f4bd17a8a4ccca4de4ed0056a7792" type="application">
    <folder name="data objects" id="id-1a54c7e5da3f46c1b129f6b8d854a643">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Entoli-agent" id="id-2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d">
        <documentation>An entoli-agent is an explicitly defined, autonomous software entity within the Entoli ecosystem that, on the basis of a formal agent-charter and agent-contract, executes specific tasks, produces Entoli artifacts or delivers information, and always operates within a demarcated agent-boundary and according to applicable governance.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Agent-contract" id="id-3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e">
        <documentation>An agent-contract formally defines the intent (agent-capability) of the entoli-agent, the input it expects and the output (artifact) it creates or answers it gives, as well as the policies and constraints under which those capabilities are accessible.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Agent-capability" id="id-3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c">
        <documentation>An agent-capability is an explicitly callable function of an entoli-agent, recorded in an agent-contract. Agent-capability is a concrete sub-type of Entoli-capability: it is an Entoli-capability as realised and exposed by one specific agent through its contract.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Artifact" id="id-8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d">
        <documentation>An Entoli artifact is a durable, explicit and transferable recording of result or decision-making, that represents value within a value stream phase and can serve as input for subsequent work.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Artifact-function-axis" id="id-7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c">
        <documentation>The artifact-function-axis is a classification axis for Entoli artifacts that describes which function an artifact fulfils in the decision and value chain within the ecosystem.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Entoli-concept" id="id-039879aaece041a79c21a4d4cbb43d85">
        <documentation>An Entoli concept is the ecosystem-level synonym for Element. Every explicitly defined, coherent and reusable unit of meaning within the Entoli ecosystem is an element in the semantic graph of the canon. The term Entoli-concept is used to refer to any such element by name within ecosystem communication.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Execution" id="id-4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f">
        <documentation>An Execution is a runtime instance derived from an Execution Step Specification. It is the container in which an Instruction Set is carried out and in which Execution Steps are recorded.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Development phase" id="id-0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f">
        <documentation>Development phase is a classification axis that describes in which phase of the formation of work a role or intervention takes place. It positions the work in the chain from intention to operationalisation.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Intervention Type" id="id-1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a">
        <documentation>Intervention Type is the classification axis that defines how an Entoli agent intervenes on artifacts or their meaning.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Prompt" id="id-6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b">
        <documentation>A prompt is a concrete, textual or structured expression of a call or instruction to an entoli-agent, formulated in natural language or another representation form, but itself not forming a canonical part of the agent-contract.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Mode of operation" id="id-2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b">
        <documentation>Mode of operation is a classification axis that describes whether an entoli-agent intervenes in content or in the conditions under which content work can take place.&#xD;
&#xD;
POSITIONS &#xD;
- Content — the agent operates primarily on the substantive content of its input&#xD;
- Representation-transforming — the agent transforms the form or format of existing content&#xD;
- Conditional — the agent applies rules or conditions to determine its output</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Execution Step" id="id-5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a">
        <documentation>An Execution Step is a runtime record of what occurred at one position within an Execution. It is the instance that came into being when an Execution Step Specification was executed using an Instruction set as LLM input.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Semantic Scope" id="id-a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7">
        <documentation>A Semantic Scope is an explicitly defined, context-specific subset of the Semantic Model, selected for use by a specific agent contract or coordination context.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Semantic Model" id="id-a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6">
        <documentation>The Semantic Model is the complete, authoritative representation of all concepts and their relationships as established in the Entoli Canon.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Source-regime" id="id-9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e">
        <documentation>Source-regime is the classification axis that specifies, per agent-contract, which source space the agent may use during an execution, and thus how strictly derivation is bounded. The source-regime records the concrete rules for that position: which sources are valid, which are excluded, and whether interpretation or synthesis is permitted.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Value stream" id="id-5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e">
        <documentation>A value stream is an explicitly defined chain of value-creating steps that together lead to a recognisable result, and that gives direction to which artifacts, entoli-agents and decisions contribute to that value.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Value stream phase" id="id-4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d">
        <documentation>A value stream phase is a logically demarcated, value-creating unit within a value stream, in which a specific type of value comes into being, recognisable via explicit artifacts and quality criteria, independent of the manner of execution.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Normative artifact" id="id-e94775ce53da4b1487ade465168978ea">
        <documentation>A normative artifact is a document that prescribes how something must be or be done within the Entoli ecosystem.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Interpretation Mode" id="id-ed6c25557b1944309960b3ed32f2463e">
        <documentation>Interpretation Mode is the classification axis that specifies, per agent-intent, within what interpretive boundaries the LLM is permitted to operate when executing the task. It defines what the LLM is allowed to do, what it is forbidden to do, and what output form is expected.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Execution Step Specification" id="id-c8ff51438a5a43e0b2d9f5eb28840a43">
        <documentation>An Execution Step Specification is a predefined, configuration-level description of execution behavior. It specifies which Agent-intent is to be invoked and under what conditions, defined independently of runtime state and independently of LLM input.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Instruction Set" id="id-fd42a7d492c64cbe8d99c4b403501755">
        <documentation>An Instruction Set is an ordered collection of Instructions assembled by coordination and handed off to the execution layer as a single unit of work.</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Interpretation Mode" id="id-74040cc1deff420a8806a4db047c18b8">
        <documentation>Interpretation Mode is the classification axis that specifies, per agent-intent, within what interpretive boundaries the LLM is permitted to operate when executing the task. It defines what the LLM is allowed to do, what it is forbidden to do, and what output form is expected.&#xD;
&#xD;
POSITIONS INTERPRETATION MODE&#xD;
- Explotarory&#xD;
- Explanatory&#xD;
- Structure-realising — produces structural artefacts (templates, schemas, patterns)&#xD;
- Normative — produces artefacts that establish norms, rules, or obligations&#xD;
- Realising — produces implementations, code, or deployable artefacts&#xD;
- Evaluative — produces assessments, reports, or validation outcomes&#xD;
- Ordering — produces ranked or ordered artefacts&#xD;
- Validating — produces validation or conformity findings</documentation>
      </element>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:DataObject" name="Template" id="id-01a25f721c954045b2c20d63486f16f1">
        <documentation>A template is a pre-structured pattern that defines the expected form, sections, or skeleton of a business artifact. It does not prescribe content but provides the structural starting point from which a concrete business artifact can be created. Templates are derived from or aligned with business artifacts and ensure consistency in artifact production across agents and value stream phases.</documentation>
      </element>
    </folder>
    <folder name="application services" id="id-6e3b80b1fc324964a12ef62f53db2397">
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ApplicationService" name="Assemble Instruction Set (with traceability)" id="id-36f6c98ee96744e58d64dd46d233a702"/>
      <element xsi:type="archimate:ApplicationService" name="Define Agent Capabilities" id="id-85df2ac646fe46588e3ae410658daa91"/>
