    <folder name="principles" id="id-5e6ca71ebf4f4d0bbd8e4f3e96abd504">
      <folder name="organization" id="id-166555db23c742769bb1ba76b5feb750">
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="We apply Architectural Thinking" id="id-12ad7fd7167640ebb66b5e8c82918c52">
          <documentation>**Short description**  &#xD;
Although AI is disruptive for the IT market, we continue to work according to existing architectural principles.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Rationale&#xD;
Like earlier technological leaps (for example from machine language to higher-level programming languages), AI does not make IT simpler, but more complex. The fundamental challenges of software development — separation of concerns, maintainability, testability — remain and even become more important.&#xD;
&#xD;
This principle guards against falling into the trap of &quot;magic&quot; solutions where architecture is forgotten. AI is a powerful tool, but not a replacement for structural thinking.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Implications&#xD;
&#xD;
**For system design**:&#xD;
- We continue to think in terms of concerns and responsibilities&#xD;
- Separation of concerns remains leading (also for AI components)&#xD;
- New technology changes tooling and implementation, not the architectural frame of thinking&#xD;
&#xD;
**For development**:&#xD;
- We avoid &quot;magic&quot; solutions without a clear architecture&#xD;
- Complexity is managed through structure and clarity, not cleverness&#xD;
- We explicitly document decisions and trade-offs&#xD;
&#xD;
**For governance**:&#xD;
- Architecture reviews remain mandatory, also for AI components&#xD;
- Existing quality gates and quality requirements remain in force&#xD;
- We apply proven patterns before introducing new ones&#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Good** ✓&#xD;
- Explicitly bounding and documenting agent capabilities in charters&#xD;
- Separating prompts from business logic and data&#xD;
- Clearly isolating state management and side effects&#xD;
- Designing agents according to the single responsibility principle&#xD;
&#xD;
**Bad** ✗&#xD;
- Deploying a large AI model without a clear capability boundary&#xD;
- Mixing prompts with configuration, data and business rules in one file&#xD;
- &quot;The AI will figure it out&quot; without architectural consideration&#xD;
- Agents with vague, overlapping responsibilities and unclear boundaries</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="We are sovereign" id="id-38e1a3641805465c920243442bf2f120">
          <documentation>**Short description**  &#xD;
We are sovereign: we make our own decisions and do not make ourselves structurally dependent on external parties, vendors or closed ecosystems.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Rationale&#xD;
This principle safeguards that conviction at the organisational level and protects our independence and autonomy. By choosing sovereignty, we retain control over our own direction, knowledge and development.&#xD;
&#xD;
In a world where vendor lock-in and dependency on large platforms keep growing, this principle protects our freedom to choose what is best for our own situation.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Implications&#xD;
&#xD;
**For decision-making**:&#xD;
- We deliberately choose open standards and open-source tools&#xD;
- In vendor choices, long-term autonomy weighs more heavily than short-term convenience&#xD;
- We build and maintain core knowledge ourselves rather than fully outsourcing it&#xD;
&#xD;
**For architecture and technology**:&#xD;
- Vendor lock-in is actively avoided&#xD;
- We prefer solutions where we fully control data and logic&#xD;
- We continue to develop and innovate ourselves, even when that requires more effort&#xD;
- We are investigating the possibility of developing our own LLM to retain full control over our AI capabilities&#xD;
&#xD;
**For organisation and culture**:&#xD;
- We invest in our own knowledge and skills&#xD;
- We document and share knowledge internally so we are not dependent on individual people or external parties&#xD;
- We take responsibility for our own course&#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Good** ✓&#xD;
- Using Linux as an operating system instead of proprietary alternatives&#xD;
- Choosing open-source databases with a strong community and standards&#xD;
- Developing and managing agents ourselves within Entoli rather than depending on closed-source AI platforms&#xD;
- Using Git with our own repository management instead of full dependency on a single cloud provider&#xD;
&#xD;
**Bad** ✗&#xD;
- Going all-in on a single cloud provider without an exit strategy&#xD;
- Fully outsourcing critical business logic without retaining knowledge internally&#xD;
- Using proprietary formats with no conversion path to open standards&#xD;
- Becoming dependent on a single vendor for all tooling with no alternatives</documentation>
        </element>
        <element xsi:type="archimate:Principle" name="We prove first (then scale)" id="id-50597cb2e8e147b7a6e9a7429233aba5">
          <documentation>**Short description**  &#xD;
We first prove that something has value, before trying to make it big.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Rationale&#xD;
In an early stage, scale is often a distraction. The real risk is not that something fails to scale, but that it has no meaningful value. By focusing on value first, we learn what really matters and avoid wasting energy on scalability problems that may never become relevant.&#xD;
&#xD;
This principle guards our focus and prevents over-engineering and premature optimisation. It forces us to work with small, real signals rather than large assumptions.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Implications&#xD;
&#xD;
**For product development**:&#xD;
- Ideas are first substantively tested with a small, concrete audience&#xD;
- We build for a concrete use case, not for &quot;the market&quot; in general&#xD;
- Small, real signals (usage, feedback) weigh more heavily than large assumptions&#xD;
&#xD;
**For architecture**:&#xD;
- Scalability follows from value, not the other way around&#xD;
- We build simple and extensible, not complex and &quot;future-proof&quot;&#xD;
- We refactor towards scale when it proves necessary, not in advance&#xD;
&#xD;
**For decision-making**:&#xD;
- Decisions are made based on learning and feedback, not on ambition or assumptions&#xD;
- We invest in experiments and prototypes before making large commitments&#xD;
- We accept that not every idea scales, and that is okay&#xD;
&#xD;
### Examples&#xD;
&#xD;
**Good** ✓&#xD;
- Testing a new agent first with one concrete use case and improving iteratively&#xD;
- Manually walking through a workflow before building automation&#xD;
- Publishing a knowledge article and gathering feedback before producing a whole series&#xD;
- A simple file-based implementation before introducing a database&#xD;
&#xD;
**Bad** ✗&#xD;
- Immediately setting up a complex microservices architecture for a first prototype&#xD;
- Building a scalable database solution before knowing whether anyone uses the product&#xD;
- Developing a general framework without a concrete use case&#xD;
- Investing in performance optimisation before knowing whether the feature has value&#xD;
&#xD;
---&#xD;
&#xD;
## Coherence and Implementation&#xD;
&#xD;
These three principles reinforce each other:&#xD;
&#xD;
**Sovereignty** guards our independence and autonomy.  &#xD;
**Architectural Thinking** guards our coherence and structure.  &#xD;
**Value before scale** guards our focus and learning.&#xD;
&#xD;
Together they form a foundation for how we work: independent, structured and focused on real value.&#xD;
&#xD;
### Conflicts between principles&#xD;
In practice, principles can sometimes clash:&#xD;
- Sovereignty can lead to more complexity (doing everything ourselves vs. buying)&#xD;
- Architectural Thinking can slow things down (structure takes time)&#xD;
- Value before scale can lead to technical debt (learning fast vs. building robustly)&#xD;
&#xD;
In such dilemmas:&#xD;
1. Make the trade-off explicit&#xD;
2. Deliberately choose which principle takes precedence in this specific situation&#xD;
3. Document the choice and the rationale&#xD;
4. Evaluate afterwards whether the choice was right</documentation>
        </element>
      </folder>
    </folder>
  </folder>
